For the remaining questions, we will consider changing ML's type system in the following way: We allow a function that takes a tuple argument ğšğŸ· * ğšğŸ¸ * ... ğšğš— to be called not only with a tuple of that exact type but also with wider tuples ğšğŸ· * ğšğŸ¸ * ... ğšğš— * ğš(ğš—+ğŸ·) * ğš(ğš—+ğŸ¸) * .... The typing rule for such calls is that the first n parts of the tuple must still have the "right" type for the call and the "extra" parts each need to have some type, but any type is fine. The evaluation rule for such calls is that the tuple argument is fully evaluated (including the "extra" parts) and the extra parts are simply inaccessible (ignored) by the function called.

Note the only typing rule we change is the one for function calls.

We assume the goals of the ML type system ("what it aims to prevent") are unchanged except that is okay to use these "too-wide tuples".

